        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(gateway): register SIGHUP handler for daemon signal hygiene",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nRegister a SIGHUP handler in the gateway run-loop as standard daemon hygiene.\n\nA long-running daemon process should never terminate on SIGHUP (terminal hangup). Previously, the gateway had no SIGHUP listener, so Node.js applied the default OS behavior: terminate with exit code 129. Now SIGHUP is logged and ignored, matching standard Unix daemon practice (equivalent to `nohup`).\n\nSIGTERM and SIGINT remain the supported shutdown signals.\n\n> **Note:** This is defensive hardening. The SSH disconnect outage reported in #84249 involves a SIGTERM path from the TUI/systemd lifecycle chain, which is a separate concern. This PR ensures the gateway does not crash on any stray SIGHUP regardless of how it was launched.\n\n## Changes\n\n| File | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `run-loop.ts` | Add one-line SIGHUP handler: log & ignore |\n| `run-loop.test.ts` | Two tests: SIGHUP ignored unconditionally; SIGHUP ignored with supervisor markers set |\n\n## Tests\n\n```\n$ node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/cli/gateway-cli/run-loop.test.ts\n ✓ cli ../../src/cli/gateway-cli/run-loop.test.ts (30 tests) 75ms\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  30 passed (30)\n```\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed**: Gateway process terminates with exit 129 on SIGHUP because no signal handler is registered. Any process that receives a stray SIGHUP (e.g. from a parent terminal closing) would crash.\n- **Real environment tested**: macOS arm64, Node.js `v24.10.0`, OpenClaw `2026.5.18 (50a2481)`.\n\n### Step 1: Verify main branch has no SIGHUP handler\n\n```\n$ grep -n 'SIGHUP' src/cli/gateway-cli/run-loop.ts\n(no matches — SIGHUP handler is missing on main)\n```\n\n### Step 2: Verify fix branch has unconditional SIGHUP ignore\n\n```\n$ grep -n 'SIGHUP' src/cli/gateway-cli/run-loop.ts\n127:    process.removeListener(\"SIGHUP\", onSighup);\n713:    gatewayLog.info(\"signal SIGHUP received; ignoring (daemon survives terminal hangup)\");\n758:  process.on(\"SIGHUP\", onSighup);\n```\n\n### Step 3: Real signal delivery — process WITH handler (fix)\n\n```\n$ node gateway-sighup-test.mjs &\n[PID: 98551]\n\n$ kill -HUP 98551\nProcess still alive ✓\n\n$ kill -HUP 98551  # send again\nProcess still alive after second SIGHUP ✓\n\n$ kill -TERM 98551  # clean shutdown\nProcess exited with code 0 ✓ (graceful shutdown)\n```\n\n### Step 4: Contrast — process WITHOUT handler (main branch)\n\n```\n$ node gateway-no-handler.mjs &  # no SIGHUP handler\n[PID: 98612]\n\n$ kill -HUP 98612\nProcess terminated with exit code 129 ← CRASH (default SIGHUP action)\n```\n\n- **Evidence after fix**: SIGHUP is unconditionally logged and ignored. Process survives multiple SIGHUP signals and only stops on SIGTERM.\n- **What was not tested**: The SSH disconnect outage in #84249 involves SIGTERM from the TUI/systemd lifecycle, not raw SIGHUP. That path requires a separate fix targeting the TUI session teardown chain.\n",
        "branch": "fix/sighup-handler-84249",
